g.text: The compiler compiles the code into assembly (.s), which is a symbolic representation of the ‘machine’ language. Assembly is the languages closest to the ‘Machine language’ and helps to understand how and what a computer is performing. Understanding of this language can help to optimize on performance and memory use. It can be seen as an intermediate language.

g.title: Folded Corner.85
g.desc: The linker ‘links’ multiple object files with each other resu...

g.text: The linker ‘links’ multiple object files with each other resulting in a single executable file. It ‘links’ the object files by replacing the undefined references with the correct addresses. Different forms of linking:· Static linking, which means copying a static library (.lib in Windows and .a files in Linux) or single object file(s) directly into the final executable file. · Dynamic linking, which means a small sub-set (containing names of variables & functions and information from the .dll ) of the dynamic library (.dll in Windows, .so in Linux) are copied into the final executable. The linking occurs at run time when everything is loading into memory.Static vs Dynamic libraries:· Physical memory(RAM) and disk-space: for static libraries each executable needs a copy of that library. In terms of physical memory(RAM) and disk-space this is very insufficient. Dynamic libraries make it possible to load the library in to memory only once. Multiple executables can link to this dynamically.· Compilation: a change within a static library means that recompilation is needed of the final executable. For dynamic libraries this is not the case.· Vulnerability: a dynamic library resides outside of the final executable and there for it could happen that it becomes corrupt more easily. E.g. when it is deleted accidently by the user. With a static library this is not possible.· Performance: static libraries do not have to make external calls, because the binary code is included in a single executable. This brings advantage in execution speed in comparison to dynamic libraries.

g.title: Folded Corner.44
g.desc: Linking Abstract Object files contain stub references (usuall...

g.text: LinkingAbstractObject files contain stub references (usually in the form of function entry point addresses or explicit, human-readable names) to the functions they call. Then, the linker looks at each library and object file, finds the references (, throws an error if a function definition couldn't be found), then substitutes the stub references with actual "call this function" machine code instructions. (Yes, this is largely simplified, but without you asking about a specific architecture and a specific compiler/linker, it's hard to tell more precisely...).Reference: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/19464265/how-exactly-does-linking-workIn depthThe linker performs two main tasks:Relocation: An object file consists of different sections. Each section contains a name, size and often data. The linker takes the code and data sections of each object file and merges them into the code and data sections of the final executable file. It is called relocation, because the (code and data) addresses of each individual object file can be different within the final executable. Symbol resolution: An object file contains a symbol table. This table contains symbol addresses, types (e.g. T = Text, U = Undefined), and names (e.g. variable or function names). There are two main types of symbols: · Local: a symbol that other translation units cannot use (e.g. static). · External (defined and undefined): a symbol declared as extern in C, which is public accessible by other translation units. The linkers job is to resolve all the undefined symbols and thus find the definition for each function and variable. Is the name of the undefined symbol used to find the definition in other object files?Reference: https://medium.com/@antriani.s/how-do-linkers-work-b572274e295b

g.title: Folded Corner.108
g.desc: Binary code – in depth The linker can generate different exec...

g.text: Binary code – in depthThe linker can generate different executable ‘formats’. This final executable will be loaded by the loader of a certain operating system and executed.Comparing .bin, .elf and .hex:· .bin is the purest binary machine code. It does not need any translation/interpretation by the target (e.g. NRF52840 microcontroller).· .hex is the hexadecimal representation of the binary code. It is composed of records, containing information as: number of bytes, start addresses, checksums, data, etc. The hex format makes the binary more readable for human interpretation. The target will interpret .hex into binary and loads it into flash memory.· .elf is an target independent format that the linker can generate. It needs a so-called ‘object copy’ instruction from the linker to generate .bin or .hex format. Arm targets cannot directly interpret .elf files, so that’s why an object copy is need. An .elf file contains debug symbols, data, loader information, etc. The .elf will provide an target independent intermediate format and allows to debug the target.
